time independent relation
TimeIndependentRelation
comment:
The collection of all Relations whose extentions (see relationExtension) do not change over time. A relation RELN is an instance of TimeIndependentRelation if and only if there is no sequence SEQ and times T1 and T2 such that RELN holds among SEQ at T1 but not at T2. Thus, if RELN holds of a given sequence at any time, it holds of it at all times.

Examples of time-independent relations include greaterThan, which relates numbers and other ScalarIntervals eternally, and simultaneousWith, which relates TimePoints eternally.

Note that a relation whose extension is necessarily empty, such as is neither identical to nor distinct from, trivially qualifies as time-independent.

Cf. TemporallyQualifiableRelation.

A specialization of Translation_NoLocationChange. Each instance of Translation_RoundTrip represents one round trip event. That is, an instance of Translation_RoundTrip is a complete translational movement that begins and ends in the same place (thus, the fromLocation and toLocation of the round trip are identical). However, a round trip is usually a discontinuous motion (cf. Movement_TranslationProcess). In the simplest case, it has exactly one outboundLegOfRoundTrip and exactly one inboundLegOfRoundTrip (qq.v.), and the trip breaks at the destination_RoundTrip, which is the place that the traveller visits in between the two legs of the journey. Thus, in addition to a fromLocation and toLocation, an instance of Translation_RoundTrip also has an origin_RoundTrip and destination_RoundTrip. The origin_RoundTrip is just the same as the fromLocation and toLocation. Note: to describe a multi-stop `round trip', instead of using Translation_RoundTrip one can represent it as a circuit composed of a series of one-way legs.

By contrast, such flush surface regions are translating relative to each other during instances of Sliding_Generic. Typical examples include objects sliding, slipping, or skidding. An instance of RelationshipType and a specialization of TemporallyQualifiableRelation. Each instance of TemporalExistenceRelation is a relation that is "contemporary" in one of its arguments places or, if it is a function, in the resultIsa.

That is, if RELN is an instance of this collection, then either

RELN is a predicate and there is at least one i (0 < i <= N), such that if

(RELN ARG-1, ..., ARG-N)<MT TIME PAR>

holds, then the temporal extent of ARG-i must subsume TIME. Or,

RELN is a function such that RELN denotes a value only if

(i) there exists an argument place that is "contemporary" in the way described in the condition for predicates -- RELN will only denote if the temporal extent of the argument in the contemporary spot subsumes the time index of the assertion in which RELN appears as a denotational term. Or,

(ii) the temporal extent of the assigned value for a given sequence of arguments to RELN subsumes the time index of the assertion in which RELN appears as a denotation term.

For further information about these conditions see the comments on TemporalExistenceRelation and CoexistenceRelation.

A surface of revolution is a surface generated by rotating a planar curve about an axis contained in the same plane. The generating curve is called a generatrix and may be either closed or open, bounded or unbounded. Here are some examples of surfaces of revolution:

1. A Spheroid is obtained by rotating an Ellipse about either its major or minor axes. In the first case, the surface is a ProlateSpheroid, while in the second case, the surface is an OblateSpheroid. If the Ellipse is a Circle, the surface is a Sphere.

2. A TorusSurface is obtained by rotating a Circle about a line which is in the same plane as the circle, but is separated from it.

See also the predicates axisOfSurfaceOfRevolution and generatrixOfSurfaceOfRevolution.

create a file in the /tmp directory with the same name and then symlink that file to a file to which the user does not have write permissions faults
comment: SymlinkFault_Overwrite is an attribute of some instances of ComputerProgram_CW. A program has a SymlinkFault_Overwrite if when running it creates files with predictable filenames and world write permissions in the /tmp directory. This fault allows a user to create a file in the /tmp directory with the same name and then symlink that file to a file to which the user does not have write permissions. When the malicious user or another user executes the program, it follows the symlink and overwrites the protected file. As with other faults, the severity of SymlinkFault_Overwrite depends on the privilege level under which the exploited program is running. If the program runs at root, for instance, when creating the /tmp files, then the malicious user can overwrite any known file on the computer.

For example, an instance of SystemOfDevices consisting of instances of Computer would be an instance of SystemOfDevices_Communications if part of the purpose in constructing the system of computers were to allow communication among users of them or if communication among users of them via the system were necessary to fulfill the primary function of the system. Note that some groupMembers of any instance of SystemOfDevices_Communications will be instances of CommunicationDevice (often of the same type) and all 'links' among these members will allow the transfer of information appropriate to the type(s) of communication devices. comment: The collection of all acts of transcription. If PERFORMER is the performer of a TranscriptionEvent, TRANSCRIBE, then PERFORMER brings it about that the information (to some degree of specificity) contained in the informationOrigin, ORIGIN, of TRANSCRIBE comes to be contained in the informationDestination, DESTINATION, of TRANSCRIBE. ORIGIN and DESTINATION must both instantiate instances of AbstractInformationStructure (at times during TRANSCRIBE), and some of the AbstractInformationStructures instantiated by ORIGIN must come to be instantiated by DESTINATION, during TRANSCRIBE. TranscriptionEvents are distinguished from other sorts IBTGeneration_Replication (such as PhotocopyingADocument) in that, generally, the performer of a TranscriptionEvent is aware (sometime during that event) of the AbstractInformationStructures instantiated by ORIGIN, and is also aware (sometime during TRANSCRIBE) of the AbstractInformationStructures that come to be instantiated by DESTINATION. TranscriptionEvents are typically composed of many subevents that are also TranscriptionEvents. For example, if TRANSCRIBE is the transcription of an audio tape, ORIGIN, to the tablet DESTINATION, then TRANSCRIBE will typically be composed of other TranscriptionEvents in which small segments of the whole tape are informationOrigins in transcription events that have small portions of the tablet as informationDestinations.

underspecified path fault

comment: An OperatingSystem has this fault if, in those situations where it is called upon to retrieve or execute some file without being given the file's full location (path), it looks for the file in a manner that makes insertion and execution of trojan programs a fairly trivial matter. Note that both UnixOSes and MSWindowsOperatingSystems may have this fault. In UnixOSes the fault is usually due to the OS's including the user's current directory in the $PATH environment variable; this makes it easy for a malicious user to insert malicious programs called 'ls', 'more', 'grep', etc. In the case of MSWindowsOperatingSystems, the fault is usually due to the order in which the OS searches the filesystem in looking for the relevant file (this search may or may not include checking the user's HKEY_CURRENT_USER\Environment\Path registry setting). One common and very dangerous fault of this kind is the NTShellPathUnderspecificationFault. Commands executed via exploitation of an UnderspecifiedPathFault are executed with the privileges of the user running the command.

Since some roles are played by multiple individuals during the course of some situation, these predicates let you specify the times at which certain individuals play certain roles via our temporal qualification framework. Often the instances of this collection will be "present tense" versions of non-temporally qualifiable role predicates. For instance, actingInDramaticPerformance is an instance of this collection and (actingInDramaticPerformance PERF ACTOR)<MT T P> holds just in case during the time interval T ACTOR is playing the castMembers role in PERF. comment:
A specialization of MultiDimensionalUnitOfMeasure (q.v.). Each instance of UnitOfRatio is a function that returns an instance of RatioQuantity (q.v.) when applied to a number or other NumericInterval (or pair of numeric-intervals). Each unit-of-ratio can (at least in principle) be derived as the result of applying PerFn (q.v.) to two units-of-measure.

For example, MilesPerGallon is a unit-of-ratio that is equal to (PerFn Mile Gallon_US). And (MilesPerGallon 40) (e.g.) is equal to the result of dividing the Distance 40-miles by the Volume 1-gallon. Thus:

(MilesPerGallon 40) = ((PerFn Mile Gallon_US) 40) = (QuotientFn (Mile 40) (Gallon_US 1)) .

Specializations of UnitOfRatio include UnitOfRate and UnitOfPressure.

label: spatially bounded thing
SpatiallyBoundedThing
comment:
A specialization of SpatiallyContinuousThing (q.v.). This is the collection of self-connected (i.e. one-piece) spatial things that are fully bounded geometrically. In the case of a line, this means having two end-points (see LinearObject_Bounded). In the case of a surface, this means having a perimeter or hole (see SurfaceRegion_Bounded). In the case of a solid, this means having a closed external surface or an internal cavity.

Since every known tangible body is spatially-bounded, the intersection of PartiallyTangible and SpatiallyContinuousThing is asserted to be a specialization of SpatiallyBoundedThing in the NaivePhysicsMt. It is not asserted in any "top" microtheory (such as the UniversalVocabularyMt), however, so as not to rule out a priori the possibility of a plenum universe (which is what the ancient Greek philosopher Parmenides, for one, believed of the actual universe).

Cf. SpatiallyUnboundedThing and SpatiallySemiBoundedThing.

comment: In a turning movement, an attacking force seeks to pass around and avoid the enemy's main force, then secure an objective deep in the hostile rear area that causes the enemy to move out of its current positions or divert major forces to meet the threat. A commander uses this choice of maneuver when the opportunity exists to seize vital areas in the hostile rear before the main enemy force can withdraw or receive support or reinforcements. A supporting effort may be required to fix the enemy, such as an envelopment. However, a turning movement is not always accompanied by a supporting effort. A turning movement differs from an envelopment because the force conducting a turning movement is normally out of supporting range of the main body but is within supporting distance. This choice of maneuver frequently transitions from the attack into an exploitation or pursuit. Although the turning force is frequently the main force, it may not always be. FM100-40.

A collection of collections and a specialization of ExistingStuffType. Instances are subcollections of PartiallyTangible whose membership is based only on the physical and/or chemical composition of their instances. TangibleStuffCompositionType does not have as instances collections whose instances are determined _solely_ by the physical state they are in -- for that, see TangibleStuffStateType. However, many substances that chemically break down before melting (e.g. FattyTissue) _are_ included in this collection, even though they exist solely in one physical state. The collection Water is an instance of TangibleStuffCompositionType, as instances of Water are all pieces of substance with the chemical composition H20. On the other hand , the collection of all pieces of ice (i.e. (SolidFn Water)) is not a TangibleStuffCompositionType, because membership in that collection depends on the substance's composition _and_ on its physical state. TalcumPowder is not an instance of this collection because a fused mass of the substance would no longer be powder, but would still be of the same TangibleStuffCompositionType. Further instances of TangibleStuffCompositionType are Nylon, GasolineFuel, FattyTissue, Nitrogen, and Glass. An important specialization of this collection is ChemicalSubstanceType -- those substance types defined solely by their chemical formulae.

label: translational vibration
Vibration-Translational
comment: The center of mass of an objectMoving in a Vibration_Translational periodically translates back and forth due as a function of some location dependent potential. For example, a ball bounces up and down. When the ball is high its potential energy is high and rising kinetic energy is low and decreasing. Eventually kinetic energy peters out and the ball comes to a stop turns around and starts heading downward. This kind of motion applies to non-circular elements of Orbiting, mass spring systems, swinging pendulums. A bus shuttling to and fro (see Translation_BackAndForth) is not an exemplar since there is no equilibrium position for the bus. Note that Vibration_Translational is different from vibrational movement due to shape change. For example, if you hit a bell it vibrates by changing its shape periodically. Its center of mass does not necessarily move back and forth. Therefore a bell ringing which does not also rock back and forth is not an objectMoving in a Vibration_Translational. Note that the most typical exemplars of Vibration_Translational (e.g. a pendulum swinging) are also elements of Translation_NoLocationChange. However, not changing location is not a necessary property since, e.g. a ball bouncing its way across a stage is clearly an element of Vibration_Translational and does undergo location change.

label: system role predicate

comment: A specialization of Role. Each instance of SystemRolePredicate is a binary predicate that relates an agent (an instance of Agent_PartiallyTangible) to a functional system (an instance of FunctionalSystem), specifying a functional role that the agent plays in the system. Unless there are contextual or system-specific constraints to the contrary (cf. FixedFunctionalSystem), an agent may play multiple roles within the same system, and may indeed play different roles at different times in the history of the system. Each instance of SystemRolePredicate is associated with a certain set of expectations (see expected_ToBe and amenable_ToBe) about how an agent who has a role will behave while playing the role, and also with a set of expected capabilities that the agent playing the role must have or maintain during the time it plays that role. As a rule, these expectations may be satisfied by an agents's taking any number of actions.

URL
UniformResourceLocator
comment: A specialization of ContactInfoString. Instances of this collection are commonly called "web addresses". Each instance of UniformResourceLocator (often abbreviated "URL") is a string that can be used to specify an object on the Internet, such as a WebPage_CW or InternetNewsgroup. The first part of a URL is the name of a particular InternetProtocol, such as http, ftp, news, telnet, or mailto, and is followed by a colon. The part immediately following the first colon is different for each protocol, but generally is a string of characters identifying a file location, a username, and/or a password. Some URLs have a third part, consisting of '?' or '#' followed by a query string or the name of a location within a web page. Examples include ftp://ftp.downlodes.com/pub/stuff/file.zip, http://www.myorg.org/index.html, news:alt.hypertext, mailto:santa@northpole.com.

A specialization of both Conveying_Generic and Translation_Complete (qq.v.), instances of which are events in which one or more objects transport one or more other objects. Each instance of TransportationEvent is an event in which an object (in the role of transporter) aids in the translational movement of another object (having the role of transportees), so that both objects move together along the same complete pathway (see motionPathway_Complete). Optionally, one of these objects, or some third object moving along with them, provides the force to make the movement happen (see providerOfMotiveForce).

Examples of transportation events include automobile transportation, riding a bicycle, dogs pulling goods on a sled, a wagon with groceries rolling down a hill, a person carrying clothes in a suitcase, etc. In that last case, note that the transporter is the suitcase, not the person.

Note that the transporter in a transportation event need not be in motion relative to its destination throughout the transportation event; an automobile transportation is a single transportation event even if it has sub-events in which the driver and all of the passengers disembark while the car is parked and refueled. A single transportation event may also have more than one transporter. For example, a sofa may be transported accross a living room floor by two people working together.

Events which are not TransportationEvents include a river conveying some flotsam, the wind blowing a leaf, a conveyor belt moving a widget to the next person on an assembly line, or a walking beast of burden that is carrying nothing. The first three of these negative examples are instances of Conveying_Stationary, since the would-be transporter doesn't actually change its overall location (see conveyor_Stationary); in the fourth case the unburdened beast has no transportees and the event is an instance of AnimalWalkingProcess.

comment:
UnicodeDenotingASCIIString is the collection of ASCIIString_Standard strings (hence 7-bit clean) that may include valid Cyc Unicode escapes, and hence may denote any string of Unicode characters (see UnicodeStringFn).

Cyc's Unicode escapes are of the form &uhhhhhh; where the h's are 2 to 6 hexadecimal digits (0-9, A-F, a-f). For example, "&uA3;" denotes the "fancy L" currency symbol for Pound_GreatBritain.

See http://www.unicode.org/charts/ for the definitive encodings for all Unicode characters. http://www.htmlhelp.com/reference/html40/entities/ is easier to use, but gives only the more common characters. Note that the HTML encoding syntax differs slightly from Cyc's, but the hexadecimal values used are identical. Only hexadecimal format is supported; named entities (e.g. £) are not.

The collection of all trajectories of moving objects: each instance of Trajectory is the individual spatial region consisting of the points in space through which an object passes during a Movement_TranslationEvent. A trajectory may or may not follow some pre-existing or pre-defined path (Path_Generic). If it does follow one or more such paths, it determines a Traversal of those paths. A Trajectory is understood and defined as a spatial line with one of the two possible directions of motion along it. It is considered as being a part of some stationary background space (thus, in most contexts, a Trajectory cannot itself 'move'). Unlike a Path_Generic, a Trajectory (or a Traversal) can cross itself any number of times, and go back along itself, cycle over and over again, etc. If there is a Movement_TranslationEvent, then that event always has a Trajectory; it is linked to its Trajectory by the ActorSlots trajectory_Complete and possibly trajectory_Partial. In most contexts, a Trajectory will be a line (or rather a one-manifold) through space as traced by some designated point within the moving object (e.g., the center of gravity), but the collection Trajectory_SweptSpace is available to represent the whole space (with space and thickness) swept through by a moving object. Contrast Trajectory with Path_Generic and with Traversal.

label: top and bottom sided object
TopAndBottomSidedObject
comment: A TopAndBottomSidedObject is an object with an intrinsic TopSide and an intrinsic BottomSide. By 'intrinsic' we mean simply that there exists an established convention according to which one side is considered 'top' and the other side is considered 'bottom'. Usually the two sides in question can be reliably distinguished from one another. For example, by convention, the 'top' of a Table_PieceOfFurniture is the side on which other objects usually rest, while the 'bottom' is the side which usually touches the floor. Notice that a conventionally distinguishable bottom and top do not necessarily imply a left and right, or a front and back. A plant is a good example of the case where they do not: top and bottom can be reliably distinguished but not, ordinarily, front and back or left and right. Notice also--and this is crucial to the whole conception--that while a TopAndBottomSidedObject may well have a preferred orientation, changing this orientation does not change what counts as 'top' and what counts as 'bottom': if a car flips over on the highway its top is now facing the pavement and its bottom--the undercarriage--is now up in the air. If an entity does not obey this rule then it does not, generally speaking, count as having a distinguishable top and bottom--example: an hourglass or a book. (see also #$NoteAboutSidedObject)

A specialization of SensoryQuantity. Each instance of VisualSensoryQuantity is a sensory quality that can characterize a visual experience. For example, it might be the subjective impression of a particular shade of blue (see #$ColorSensoryPerception), a certain level of perceived brightness, or a particular subjectively-experienced shape. In short, a VisualSensoryQuantity is any property that can characterize "how a thing looks" to the experiencing subject.

label: three dimensional quantity
ThreeDimensionalQuantity
comment:
A specialization of MultiDimensionalQuantity (q.v.). Each instance of ThreeDimensionalQuantity is a quantity that is derivable as the product or ratio of three OneDimensionalQuantity(ies) (q.v.).

For example, (MetersPerSecondPerSecond 10) is a three-dimensional quantity obtainable by dividing (Meter 10) by (SecondsDuration 1), and then dividing that result by (SecondsDuration 1). And (CubicFoot 8) is a three-dimensional quantity obtainable by multiplying (Foot_UnitOfMeasure 2) by itself twice.

Each three-dimensional quantity is in principle equal to the result of applying some (reified or otherwise) ThreeDimensionalUnitOfMeasure (q.v.) to some NumericInterval (or pair of NumericIntervals). When a TwoDimensionalQuantity (q.v.) is multiplied or divided by (or divides) a OneDimensionalQuantity, the result is often (but not always) a three-dimensional quantity. (An example of an exception to this is (ProductFn (MilesPerHour 65) (HoursDuration 1)), which is equal to the one-dimensional quantity (Mile 65).

Specializations of ThreeDimensionalQuantity include Volume and Acceleration.

A subcollection of SubLAtomicTerm (q.v.) whose instances can be used to denote character-strings. In the SubL language (as in English), one can refer to a particular character-string by simply putting a pair of quotation marks around it. Semantically, what this amounts to is using a certain character-string to denote itself.

More precisely: a given SubLString STRING is a character-string such that, when it appears inside a pair of double-quotation marks, STRING is interpreted as denoting itself (i.e. STRING). The surrounding quotation-marks are not considered to be parts of STRING; rather, they are syncategorematic symbols whose role is merely to indicate that a string is being referred to. Thus, in the context of the sentence '(firstName Lenat "Doug")', the four-character string 'Doug' denotes itself: the string `Doug'.

Note that not every CharacterString is a SubLString: there are some restrictions on what characters a SubL-string can contain. Note also that SubLStrings are atomic terms (see SubLAtomicTerm and CycLAtomicTerm), as they cannot be constructed out of other SubL (or CycL) terms via the syntax (grammar) of SubL (or CycL). Thus although the string 'hotdog' can indeed be obtained from 'hot' and 'dog' via concatenation (see ConcatenateStringsFn), the syntax of SubL (or CycL) itself contains no rule that licenses such a construction (see e.g. the comments on SubLSExpression, CycLExpression, CycLTerm, CycLFormula, and various subcollections thereof). Note finally that SubLString is a "quoted-collection" (see #$quotedCollection). Thus the sentence '(isa "hotdog" SubLString)' means, just as one would expect, that the six-character string 'hotdog' (not the eight-character quote-inclusive '"hotdog"'; see above) is an instance of SubLString.

comment: TCPChorusingFault is a fault of some instances of ComputerProgram_CW. When "pinged" from another computer (ping or fping), hosts running software with this fault will issue one ACK for each stack loaded on the NIC. (ie: if five stacks are loaded, one ACK and four duplicate ACKs will be sent). The multiple ACKs create collisions on the subnet which may affect network functionality of other hosts on the subnet. With one offending host on the subnet, this TCP chorus may impact proper functioning of Samba hosts on the wire. With four TCP chorusers, an entire subnet may be rendered useless.

label: truth-function
TruthFunction
comment:
A major subcollection of Relation that subsumes the collections Predicate, LogicalConnective, and Quantifier (qq.v.). Truth-functions, or rather the expressions that represent or denote them, are used to form sentences. More precisely, any CycL expression that denotes an instance of TruthFunction (and only such an expression) can appear in the "0th" argument-position (i.e. as the term immediately following the opening parenthesis) of a CycLSentence.

The name 'TruthFunction' derives in part from the fact that the sentences thus formed (if semantically well-formed and quantificationally closed; see CycLSentence_Assertible and CycLClosedSentence) are the kind of expression that can be true or false (with respect to a given context and interpretation). Though not really functions (cf. Function_Denotational), many TruthFunctions are "truth-functional" in the sense that the truth-value of a (closed, semantically well-formed) sentence (RELN ARG1..ARGN) built using a truth-function RELN is uniquely determined (with respect to a given context) by RELN together with the argument(s) ARG1..ARGN to which it is applied. For example, the sentence (mother ChelseaClinton HillaryClinton) is made true (in the actual world) by the fact that Chelsea Clinton's mother is Hillary Clinton.

label: temporally continuous thing

comment:
A specialization of TemporalThing. Each instance of TemporallyContinuousThing CONT is a thing that occupies (see temporalExtent) or is one continuous chunk of time. More precisely: CONT temporallySubsumes (q.v.) every time-interval between its startingPoint and endingPoint. Thus, there is no time-interval between the start and end of CONT during which CONT does not exist (if a SomethingExisting) or occur (if an Event) or obtain (if a StaticSituation) or which CONT does not have as one of its timeSlices (if a TimeInterval).

For example, all Dates are temporally-continuous (see the specialization ContinuousTimeInterval), and most or all ordinary physical objects are temporally-continuous.

See also SpatiallyContinuousThing.

This is the collection of instances in which a person does a thought experiment. Carrying out a thought experiment is a technique employed extensively in philosophy but also notably
in relativistic physics and quantum mechanics. The idea is to achieve insight by
imagining a particular sort of scenario and then trying to figure out what would
or should happen or how the scenario should be evaluated. A philosophical example is the Experience
Machine: would a life in which all of your apparent experiences were simulated by
a computer hooked up to your brain be as good as one in which you have the same experiences
in the normal way? If not, then hedonism, the theory that the only intrinsically valuable thing is pleasure, is incorrect. Note that there need not
be a prior conceptual work of which such an activity is an instantiation. Thought experiments can be improvised.

A specialization of InformationBearingThing (IBT). Each instance of TextualMaterial is an IBT a significant part of whose informational content is both (i) encoded in some CommunicationConvention (q.v.), usually a Language, and (ii) represented or displayed in a spatial format. Examples include a copy of a newspaper printed in English using the Roman alphabet, a copy of a book printed in English using Braille, and a poster written in Chinese characters. Condition (i) excludes things like hardcopies of drawings, while condition (ii) excludes things like magnetic tapes containing recorded speech. A piece of textual material always involves one or more spatially-localized representations -- usually physical inscriptions (see CharacterStringToken_Inscribed) -- of CharacterStrings (q.v.). Textual materials are usually tangible objects (such as the examples given above), but are sometimes intangibles like patterns of light projecting words onto walls or screens. Specializations of TextualMaterial include OfficialDocument and NonPublishedText. Note that, while there is considerable overlap between TextualMaterial and HardcopyInformationBearingObject, these collections differ in that the latter both includes IBTs that involve no character-string representations and excludes intangibles of any sort.

The collection of all integer-denoting expressions in the CycL language that are _not_ CycL constants or NATs, but are terms of SubL, the underlying implementation language of the Cyc system. SubLIntegers are numeric strings of the Arabic decimal system (including the negative-value symbol `-', but _not_ the decimal point or scientific notation) that denote integers. Examples include the expressions `0', `12', and `-4' (which denote the integers 0, 12, and -4, respectively). Non-examples include `4.012', `(Meter 6)', `(Unity 3.3)', `:34', and `PlusInfinity'. Note that SubLInteger is a "quoted-collection" (see #$quotedCollection). Thus the sentence `(isa 12 SubLInteger)' means that the expression `12' (and not the number 12) is an instance of SubLInteger. Similarly, the assertion `(genls SubLInteger Integer)' means (not that each SubL integer is an integer, but) that each instance of SubLInteger _denotes_ an instance of Integer (see the shared #$NoteAboutUseVersusMention).

label: skolem function
SkolemFunction
comment:
A specialization of IndeterminateTermDenotingFunction and ReifiableFunction (qq.v.). SkolemFunction is a collection of system-generated functions that implement existential quantification in Cyc. Whenever someone asserts to the Knowledge Base a sentence that contains 'thereExists' (in an arg0 position), Cyc automatically creates a new instance of SkolemFunction and rewrites the assertion using that Skolem function.

For example, suppose we want Cyc to know that every animal has a birth date. So we assert the following sentence: 

  (implies
    (isa ?X Animal)
    (thereExists ?Y
      (birthDate ?X ?Y))) .

In response, Cyc automatically reifies a new unary instance of SkolemFunction (call it 'BirthDateFn') that takes any given animal to its date of birth, and then rewrites our rule using BirthDateFn instead of thereExists, as 

  (implies
    (and
      (isa ?X Animal)
      (termOfUnit ?Y (BirthDateFn ?X)))
    (birthDate ?X ?Y)) .

Note that actual Cyc-generated Skolem function names currently (02/04) consist of the prefix 'SKF-' follow by a numeral.

comment: SymlinkFault_Deletion is an attribute of some instances of ComputerProgram_CW. It is a specialization of FileDeletionFault and SymlinkFault_Overwrite. A program has a SymlinkFault_Deletion if when running it writes null to a standard file. If the file is not the expected file but rather a a symbolic link, the null will be written to the file pointed to. When the malicious user or another user executes the program, it follows the symlink and deletes the specified file. As with other faults, the severity of SymlinkFault_Overwrite depends on the privilege level under which the exploited program is running. If the program runs at root, for instance, when writing null to the standard files, then the malicious user can delete any known file on the computer.

comment:
A topology, T, on a set X is a set of subsets of X which satisfies the following closure properties:

(O1) The union of every subset of T is an element of T.

(O2) The intersection of every finite subset of T is an element of T.

Axiom (O1) implies in particular that the union of the empty set is an element of T, i.e. the empty set itself is an element of T. Similarly, axiom (O2) implies that the intersection of the empty set is an element of T, i.e. X itself, is an element of T. The elements of T are called the open sets of the topological structure defined by T on X. The Tuple, (X,T) is called a TopologicalSpace.

comment:
A collection of collections. Each instance of StuffType is a collection that is stuff-like in at least one respect. A collection COL is stuff-like just in case there is some sense of 'part' according to which every part of an instance of COL is itself an instance of COL. More precisely, for a collection to be an instance of StuffType it is sufficient that there be some spec-pred PARTPRED of parts (that is, some predicate PARTPRED for which (genlPreds PARTPRED parts) holds), such that if (isa OBJECT1 COL) and (PARTPRED OBJECT1 OBJECT2), then (isa OBJECT2 COL). Here are two examples. Consider Breathing. Take an instance of that, say a ten minute long period in which a person is breathing. Imagine some two minute snippet of that, one of its timeSlices (a spec-pred of parts). That, too, is an instance of Breathing. So Breathing is a StuffType, since all timeSlices of an instance of Breathing are also instances of Breathing.

Consider Water. Take any instance of Water -- say the water in the Pacific Ocean. Now take any portion of that water -- say a handful of it that a person scoops up near Honolulu, one of its physicalPortions (a spec-pred of parts). That handful is itself an instance of Water. Hence Water is a StuffType, in virtue of the fact that all physicalPortions of all instances Water are themselves instances of Water.

Other examples are: AspatialInformationStore, which is stuff-like with respect containsInformation; CharacterString, which is stuff-like with respect to subCharacterStrings; and List, which is stuff-like with respect to subLists. These examples are somewhat exceptional -- most StuffTypes are like the examples of Breathing and Water. See ObjectType, for the contrasting (but not disjoint) notion of being object-like.

comment: A collection of translational motion events; hence a subcollection of Movement_TranslationEvent. In any instance of Translation_NoLocationChange, the objectMoving undergoes translational motion but ends up where it started --- i.e., there is no NET movement; i.e., its fromLocation and toLocation are the same. Between the beginning and the end of a Translation_NoLocationChange, the objectMoving may visit the toLocation and the fromLocation any number of times. E.g., consider the motion of a person who is born in, and 80 years later dies in, the very same hospital, and has been there a few times in between for operations, visiting patients, etc. A less dramatic example is the motion of your car on a particular day, as it gets moved around, crosses its own path a few times, etc., but ends the day in the same place it started. Instances of Translation_NoLocationChange may be periodic or nonperiodic movements. An important subcollection of Translation_NoLocationChange is Translation_RoundTrip.

using an algorithm
UsingAnAlgorithm
type: typical human activity type at least once
comment:
A specialization of Action whose instances are events in which one or more intelligent agents (possibly software agents) accurately, completely, and "purposely" follow the steps of an Algorithm (q.v.) with respect to some input(s) (see algorithmInputs).

In using an algorithm, one is of course thereby also doing whatever it is that the algorithm is an algorithm for. For example, in following an algorithm for long division one is in fact dividing one number by another. Instances of UsingAnAlgorithm are by definition "successful" in that the algorithm in question must not be deviated from or incompletely followed.

An event in which a computer follows an algorithm (see computerProcessAlgorithms) might be an instance of UsingAnAlgorithm, but only if that event is an agentive computer process associated with some pre-existing instance of #$SoftwareAgent (see softwareAgentProcesses).

For actions in which an agent, rather than carrying out an algorithm directly, uses a device that embodies an algorithm, see Computing.

label: star convex thing
StarConvexThing
comment:
A specialization of SimplyConnectedThing (q.v.). This is the collection of "star-convex" spatial things, tangible and intangible. Each instance *CONVEX of StarConvexThing subsumes (see spatiallySubsumes) a point POINT such that the straight line-segment between POINT and any other point in *CONVEX is itself subsumed by *CONVEX.

For example, a five-point star figure and a typical printed asterisk (while not strictly convex) are both star-convex. Conversely, a swastika and a printed parenthesis are not star-convex.

An important specialization of StarConvexThing is ConvexThing.
